{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499833"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:03:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:03:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1564"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1564","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1564"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.07,0.06,0.69,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1564"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44857"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1564","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1564"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1564"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29740"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"45"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"833"},{"type":"tags","id":"1309"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"6222"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11641"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5683"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6827"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11212"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43086"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44857"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents with pain at the back of her heel for the last few months. She is part of a walking group and usually meets for 4-5km walks a couple of times a week. A few months ago, she experienced pain in her heel the morning after her walks. This kept occurring for weeks, making it very difficult to walk around her house in the mornings. The pain has now progressed and walking makes the pain in her heel worse.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her calf muscles are quite tight and the following appearance is noted (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following treatments is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Eccentric strengthening (eg. heel drop exercises)","Calf stretches (eg. lunges)","Steroid injection","Activity modification with physiotherapy strength training and load management","Surgical treatment"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a picture of \u0027Non-insertional Achilles tendinopathy\u0027 . Excessive loading on the Achilles tendon can be caused by poor footwear, hard or uneven surfaces, tight calf muscles, intensive exercise, or inadequate warm up and cool down stretches. Severity is graded from 1-4 with Grade 1 describing pain only after exertion, and Grade 4 describing pain with activities of daily living. First-line non-surgical management activity modification with physiotherapy strength training and load management. This is usually overseen by a physiotherapist. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEccentric strengthening\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Ecalf stretches\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eextracorporal shockwave therapy\u003C/strong\u003E are not next line non-surgical treatments given that she has symptoms daily. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical treatment \u003C/strong\u003Eis an option when pain fails to resolve after prolonged non-surgical management. Steroid injections into tendons with evidence of tendinopathy can result in spontaneous rupture of the affected tendon, and is cautioned against.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Activity modification with physiotherapy strength training and load management is essential for non-insertional Achilles tendinopathy"],"references":["Pearce CJ, Tan A. Non-insertional Achilles tendinopathy. EFORT Open Rev. 2017 Mar 13;1(11):383-390. doi: 10.1302/2058-5241.1.160024. PMID: 28461917; PMCID: PMC5367540.","Orthobullets. Achilles tendonitis [Internet]. Pasadena CA USA: Orthobullets; 2021 Jul 6. Available from: https://www.orthobullets.com/foot-and-ankle/7022/achilles-tendonitis"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29740"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1564"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16619"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16619"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1becf9d2-288e-4835-b2af-93776ae1551a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1becf9d2-288e-4835-b2af-93776ae1551a.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":429}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29740"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-05T08:17:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-05-05T08:17:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1564"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44857"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"creat